  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        A contour integral is just a line integral over a curve <m>C</m> in the complex plane:
        <me>
          \int_{C} f(z)\dd{z}
        </me>
        We evaluate it by parametrizing <m>C</m>:
        <me>
          \int_{a}^{b} f(z(t))z'(t)\dd{t}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Great example to go through: if <m>C</m> is the unit circle parametrized counterclockwise, and <m>n\neq-1</m> is an integer, then
        <me>
          \int_{C} z^{n}\dd{z}=0\text{.}
        </me>
        However, as an exception,
        <me>
          \int_{C} \frac{1}{z}\dd{z}=2\uppi\ii\text{.}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        <theorem>
          <title>ML Inequality</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If <m>f</m> is continuous on a smooth curve <m>C</m>, and if <m>|f(z)|\le M</m> for all <m>z</m> on <m>C</m>, then
              <me>
                \abs{\int_C f(z)\dd{z}}\le ML
              </me>,
              where <m>L</m> is the length of <m>C</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>
        
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Suppose that <m>\bv F(x,y)=(P(x,y),Q(x,y))</m> is the PÃ³lya vector field of the function <m>f(z)=P(x,y)-\ii Q(x,y)</m>.
        Then:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\oint_C f(z)\dd{z} \amp = \oint_C (P-\ii Q)(\dd{x}+\ii\dd{y})</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \qty(\oint_C P\dd{x}+Q\dd{y})+\ii\qty(\oint_C P\dd{y}-Q\dd{x})</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \qty(\oint_C\bv F\cdot\uv{t}\dd{s})+\ii\qty(\oint_C\bv F\cdot\uv{n}\dd{s})</mrow>
      </md>

      <p>
        Thus the contour integral computes BOTH the circulation AND the flux at the same time!
      </p>
    </li>

